Dimension	Azure Backup	Azure Site Recovery (ASR)	Availability Zones
Primary Purpose	Data protection and restore	Disaster recovery and business continuity	High availability within a region
Problem It Solves	Data loss, corruption, accidental deletion	Datacenter / region failure, major outages	Hardware failure, zone-level outages
Type	Backup service	Replication and failover service	Infrastructure resiliency feature
Scope	Data-centric	Application / VM-centric	Infrastructure-centric
RPO (Recovery Point Objective)	Hours (policy-based)	Minutes (near-continuous replication)	Near-zero (no data movement)
RTO (Recovery Time Objective)	High (restore time required)	Low (failover in minutes)	Near-zero
Downtime During Failure	Yes	Minimal	None
Data Loss During Failure	Possible (depends on last backup)	Very minimal	None
Replication	No continuous replication	Continuous replication	No replication
Works Across Regions	Yes (restore, CRR)	Yes (primary ‚Üí secondary region)	No (same region only)
Works Within Same Region	Yes	Limited / specific scenarios	Yes
Requires Failover	No	Yes (planned / unplanned)	No
Automatic Failover	No	Manual / orchestrated	Yes (platform-managed)
Use of Recovery Services Vault	Required	Required	Not required
Typical Workloads	VM backup, SQL, SAP HANA, File Shares	Mission-critical VMs, apps	Web apps, APIs, stateless services
Cost Model	Per protected instance + storage	Per protected instance + storage + churn	Infrastructure cost only
Backup Retention	Days to years	Not designed for long-term retention	Not applicable
Protection Against Ransomware	Yes (soft delete, immutability)	Limited	No
Regulatory Compliance Use	Yes	Yes	No
Example Scenario	Restore VM deleted by mistake	DR failover from East US to West US	App survives zone outage in East US



Dimension	RPO (Recovery Point Objective)	RTO (Recovery Time Objective)
Definition	Maximum acceptable data loss measured in time	Maximum acceptable downtime measured in time
Focus	How much data you can afford to lose	How fast the service must be restored
Time Reference	Looks backward from failure	Looks forward from failure
Measured In	Minutes, hours	Minutes, hours
Business Question	‚ÄúHow recent must the data be after recovery?‚Äù	‚ÄúHow quickly must the system be back online?‚Äù
Impact Area	Data integrity	Service availability
Example Statement	‚ÄúWe can lose up to 15 minutes of data‚Äù	‚ÄúService must be live within 30 minutes‚Äù
Influenced By	Backup frequency, replication	Automation, failover process
Typical Azure Services	Azure Backup, ASR replication	ASR, Availability Zones
Backup Impact	Higher RPO (hours)	Higher RTO (restore time)
ASR Impact	Low RPO (minutes)	Low RTO (minutes)
Availability Zones Impact	Near-zero RPO	Near-zero RTO
Cost Relationship	Lower RPO = higher cost	Lower RTO = higher cost
Used In	DR planning, compliance	SLA, business continuity planning


Task#23:

1. Create a Recovery Services Vault

Create a new Recovery Services Vault with the following details:
	‚Ä¢ Name: utkloud-rsv-<yourname> (example: utkloud-rsv-suhail)
	‚Ä¢ Region: Same region as the virtual machine (FROM POINT 2)
	‚Ä¢ Storage redundancy: GRS
	‚Ä¢ Soft Delete: Enabled
	‚Ä¢ Cross-Region Restore (CRR): Enabled
	‚Ä¢ Everything else should remain default

2. Prepare the Virtual Machine
Use any existing Azure VM or create a new one with the following constraints:
	‚Ä¢ Operating System: Windows or Linux
	‚Ä¢ VM must be:
		‚óã Running
		‚óã In the same region as the Recovery Services Vault
	‚Ä¢ Do not enable backup during VM creation

3. Configure Azure VM Backup
Enable backup for the VM using the Recovery Services Vault created above:
	‚Ä¢ Backup policy:
		‚óã Name: utkloud-vm-backup-policy
		‚óã Backup frequency: Daily
		‚óã Backup time: Choose any (Suggestion- If you are working at 1pm IST then select backup time 2pm IST)
		‚óã Retention:
			¬ß Daily retention: 10 days
	‚Ä¢ Enable backup and ensure the initial backup job completes successfully

4. Validate Backup Status
Verify the following:

	‚Ä¢ VM appears under Backup Items
	‚Ä¢ Last backup status is Completed
	‚Ä¢ Backup health status shows Healthy

5. Perform Restore Operations
Perform both restore operations below:
a. File-Level Restore
	‚Ä¢ Restore any single file from the VM
	‚Ä¢ Restore location:
		‚óã Same VM
		‚óã Alternate folder path
b. Disk Restore
	‚Ä¢ Restore only the OS disk from a recovery point
	‚Ä¢ Do not create a new VM
	‚Ä¢ Verify the disk appears under Disks in the Azure portal

6. Test Soft Delete Protection
	‚Ä¢ Attempt to stop backup and delete backup data for the VM
	‚Ä¢ Observe the Soft Deleted state
	‚Ä¢ Do not permanently delete the backup item

7. Monitoring and Validation
	‚Ä¢ Review:
		‚óã Backup jobs
		‚óã Restore jobs
